1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,997
May 2022. LUNA collapses from $80 to $0 in 72

2
00:00:04,097 --> 00:00:09,732
hours. Billions in positions across Anchor, Venus, and Aave are

3
00:00:09,832 --> 00:00:18,017
instantly undercollateralized. Liquidation bots race to clear positions, dumping collateral

4
00:00:18,117 --> 00:00:24,299
onto thin markets. Each liquidation drives prices lower. Lower prices

5
00:00:24,399 --> 00:00:30,855
trigger more liquidations. The cascade propagates across the entire DeFi

6
00:00:30,955 --> 00:00:36,408
ecosystem. By the end: $300 billion in market cap evaporated.

7
00:00:36,508 --> 00:00:41,416
This is the liquidation cascade — and it's a structural

8
00:00:41,516 --> 00:00:44,876
feature of overcollateralized lending.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,707
Welcome to QuantiFire. Liquidation cascades are one of the most

10
00:00:49,807 --> 00:00:54,439
dangerous systemic risks in DeFi. They arise from the feedback

11
00:00:54,539 --> 00:00:59,934
loop between falling prices, forced selling, and further price declines.

12
00:01:00,034 --> 00:01:05,887
Understanding the mechanics helps you position your own portfolios defensively

13
00:01:05,987 --> 00:01:09,932
and identify systemic risk building up in the market.

14
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,703
The cascade mechanism: step one — asset price drops below a

15
00:01:16,803 --> 00:01:22,403
critical level, multiple positions reach a health factor below 1. Step

16
00:01:22,503 --> 00:01:28,021
two — liquidation bots execute, selling collateral on DEXes at market

17
00:01:28,121 --> 00:01:33,639
price. Step three — that selling pressure drives prices further down.

18
00:01:33,739 --> 00:01:39,501
Step four — new positions breach the health factor threshold, triggering

19
00:01:39,601 --> 00:01:45,933
more liquidations. Repeat until price finds natural support or collateral pools

20
00:01:46,033 --> 00:01:52,121
are exhausted. The feedback amplifies because all liquidations sell the same

21
00:01:52,221 --> 00:01:57,006
collateral asset — ETH — and price impact is additive across

22
00:01:57,106 --> 00:01:59,612
hundreds of simultaneous events.

23
00:02:04,666 --> 00:02:11,965
This liquidation density map shows how much ETH collateral becomes liquidatable

24
00:02:12,065 --> 00:02:17,115
at each price level. The red bars — prices below $2,000

25
00:02:17,215 --> 00:02:23,671
— represent hundreds of millions in positions that would cascade. When

26
00:02:23,771 --> 00:02:28,635
ETH was at $2,000, a drop to $1,600 would unlock $300

27
00:02:28,735 --> 00:02:35,471
million in forced selling. That selling pushes price to $1,400, unlocking

28
00:02:35,571 --> 00:02:42,401
another $420 million. The March 2020 Black Thursday event followed exactly

29
00:02:42,501 --> 00:02:47,552
this pattern — ETH dropped 43% in 24 hours and MakerDAO

30
00:02:47,652 --> 00:02:54,389
liquidation auctions had zero bidders. The protocol ended with $4 million

31
00:02:54,489 --> 00:02:57,198
in bad debt sold for zero DAI.

32
00:02:57,266 --> 00:03:03,541
In a cascade, every second counts. Automated position management tools —

33
00:03:03,641 --> 00:03:10,713
DeFiSaver automation, Instadapp — can add collateral or reduce debt automatically

34
00:03:10,813 --> 00:03:16,733
when your health factor drops below your threshold. They move faster

35
00:03:16,833 --> 00:03:22,046
than any manual response. Set these up before you need them.

36
00:03:22,146 --> 00:03:27,447
Never rely on being able to manually respond during a cascade

37
00:03:27,547 --> 00:03:31,785
— gas prices will spike 100 times and the UI will

38
00:03:31,885 --> 00:03:36,921
be down. Final episode of Series 3: Regulatory Risk — SEC,

39
00:03:37,021 --> 00:03:43,207
FATF, MiCA, and what the evolving global regulatory framework means for

40
00:03:43,307 --> 00:03:47,014
your DeFi positions. Subscribe. QuantiFire.

